      "rationale": "Hemolysis index predictions agree within 8.3% of bench reference. Velocity field R² = 0.94 against PIV. Pressure rise within 3.7%. All acceptance criteria satisfied. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validated QoIs (velocity, pressure, hemolysis index) are directly linked to the clinical decision metric (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is computed directly from the Giersiepen–Wurzinger scalar damage integral, which is the primary regulatory decision metric. Velocity and pressure fields are intermediate QoIs that feed the damage calculation. Relevance established. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities cover the geometric configuration and operating range of the COU; differences between validation and COU conditions are documented.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at operating points spanning the COU envelope (2.5–7.5 L/min, 2500–4500 rpm). Water-analogue vs. blood differences noted and judged acceptable at MRL 2. The Giersiepen–Wurzinger model is applied assuming linear, path-independent damage accumulation — a theoretical precondition that the method is valid only under non-recirculating, monotonically loaded streamlines — but no validation activity examines whether this precondition is met in the CPB pump volute where significant recirculation zones are observed.",
      "rationale_note": "The linear damage accumulation precondition is cited as a condition of applicability of the hemolysis model yet is not tested against COU flow topology."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence to residual < 1e-5 for all transport equations at all operating points.",
      "rationale": "All five operating points converged to residual < 1e-6. Mass imbalance < 0.01%. Required level 1 achieved."
